title: Charles Dickens Museum
inscription: Dickens rented this Georgian terraced house from 25 March 1837 to December 1839. It was his first substantial home in London.
address: 48 Doughty Street, King’s Cross, Camden WC1N 2LX
lead_subject_bio: During his two‑and‑a‑half‑year stay he completed The Pickwick Papers (1837) and wrote Oliver Twist and Nicholas Nickleby. His wife Catherine and her sister Mary Hogarth lived here; Mary died suddenly in 1837, an event that deeply affected him. The house is now the Charles Dickens Museum and preserves many original manuscripts and furnishings.

title: House in Town
inscription: Dickens moved with his growing family to this house in 1839 and lived there until 1851.
lead_subject_bio: The author called it his “house in town”; he wrote parts of Barnaby Rudge and David Copperfield here. His ninth child, Dora Annie, was born and died in this house in 1851. The death and the end of the lease prompted him to move to Tavistock House.

title: Tavistock House
inscription: Dickens leased this large house from 1851 to 1860.
lead_subject_bio: He wrote Bleak House, Hard Times, Little Dorrit and A Tale of Two Cities here. The house had a garden theatre where he staged amateur performances with friends and family.

title: Furnival’s Inn
inscription: As a young journalist Dickens rented chambers in Furnival’s Inn between December 1834 and early 1837. The Inn was demolished in 1897; a brown plaque on the Prudential Building marks the spot.
lead_subject_bio: Dickens began writing The Pickwick Papers while living here. It was his first matrimonial home; after marrying Catherine Hogarth in April 1836 the couple continued to live in these chambers. The illustrator Robert Seymour met Dickens here; after disagreements about the illustrations for Pickwick he took his own life.

title: Marshalsea Prison
inscription: In February 1824 Dickens’s father John was imprisoned for debt in the Marshalsea. Twelve‑year‑old Charles lodged first in Camden and then on Lant Street (SE1) near the prison.
lead_subject_bio: Dickens’s job in a blacking factory and his visits to his family in the prison left a lasting trauma. The Marshalsea wall still survives near Borough High Street. This experience inspired prison scenes in Little Dorrit and his compassion for debtors.

title: Little Dorrit’s Church
inscription: Dickens first knew this church in 1824 when his father was in the nearby Marshalsea prison. It later appeared in his novel Little Dorrit.
address: St George the Martyr Church, Borough High Street SE1 1JA
lead_subject_bio: The church stands next to the former prison; Dickens referred to confronting “the crowded ghosts of many miserable years” by making his heroine “The Child of the Marshalsea”. A stained‑glass window inside depicts Little Dorrit.

title: Warren’s Blacking Factory
inscription: At age 12 (from 1824–1825) Dickens worked here labeling pots of blacking after his father’s imprisonment.
lead_subject_bio: The factory’s move from Hungerford Stairs to Chandos Place is marked by a plaque. Dickens’s unhappy time here, feeling abandoned by his family, profoundly influenced his portrayals of exploited children.

title: Bob Fagin
inscription: During his father’s imprisonment, Dickens lodged in a house on Lant Street belonging to the vestry clerk of St George’s Church.
lead_subject_bio: A coworker named Bob Fagin lodged with him; Dickens later used the name for the pickpocket “Fagin” in Oliver Twist. The area appears in several novels.

title: City Pickwick Club
inscription: This 18th‑century chop house is mentioned over 20 times in The Pickwick Papers and Dickens frequently drank and dined here. CAMRA records state that the top floor contains “Dickens Rooms” because the writer lived here for a time.
lead_subject_bio: The pub is the headquarters of the City Pickwick Club and hosts Dickensian gatherings. Cedric Charles Dickens, the author’s great‑grandson, helped save it from demolition. Its hidden alley‑way location retains an 18th‑century atmosphere.

title: Ye Olde Cheshire Cheese
inscription: A rebuilt 17th‑century tavern; Dickens was a regular patron.
lead_subject_bio: A Tale of Two Cities alludes to the tavern: after Charles Darnay’s acquittal, Sydney Carton leads him to a Fleet Street tavern “where Darnay was soon recruiting his strength with a good plain dinner and good wine”. The pub is celebrated for its gloomy wood‑paneled rooms, long literary associations and its eccentric talking parrot “Polly”.

title: The Daily News
inscription: Fleet Street was London’s journalism hub. In January 1846 Dickens launched and briefly edited The Daily News at No. 92 Fleet Street.
lead_subject_bio: Although he resigned after only 17 issues, the liberal newspaper reflected his political views. The building is close to Ye Olde Cheshire Cheese and other taverns he frequented.

title: Household Words
inscription: In 1850 Dickens rented offices here for his weekly journal Household Words.
address: 16 Wellington Street North, Covent Garden WC2E
lead_subject_bio: He described the building’s bow‑fronted facade as “exceedingly pretty … each giving a flood of light”. The narrow street was home to numerous newspapers; his rival G. W. Reynolds operated across the road.

title: All the Year Round
inscription: From 1859 Dickens published All the Year Round, the successor to Household Words, from this address.
address: 26 Wellington Street North, Covent Garden WC2E
lead_subject_bio: The magazine serialised A Tale of Two Cities and Great Expectations. Dickens took full financial control and lived in apartments above the office.

title: Garrick Club
inscription: The exclusive theatrical club, founded in 1831, counted Dickens among its famous 19th‑century members. He socialised with actors and fellow writers here.
lead_subject_bio: The club is noted for its theatrical library and art collection. A Reuters report in 2024 listed Dickens as one of the illustrious past members. The club (now at 15 Garrick Street) has only recently begun admitting women.

title: The Old Curiosity Shop
inscription: A timber‑framed building near Lincoln’s Inn Fields. In the 1880s a shop owner placed the words “The Old Curiosity Shop – Immortalised by Charles Dickens” on the facade to attract trade.
lead_subject_bio: The building dates from the 16th or 17th century and was known to Dickens because it lay near the Insolvency Debtors Court and John Forster’s chambers. However, the Charles Dickens Museum notes that there is no evidence the shop in his 1840 novel was based on this premises. The sign nevertheless made it a stop for Dickensian tourists.

title: St George the Martyr Church
inscription: Dickens first knew the church as a child during his father’s imprisonment in 1824; he later set key scenes of Little Dorrit here.
address: St George the Martyr Church, Borough High Street SE1 1JA
lead_subject_bio: The novel’s heroine, born in the Marshalsea, is christened in this church and later marries Arthur Clennam here. Inside the church, a stained‑glass window depicts Little Dorrit.

title: Home of the Plornish family
inscription: This cobbled courtyard in Holborn inspired the home of the Plornish family in Little Dorrit. Dickens described it as a place of decayed grandeur inhabited by poor families.
lead_subject_bio: The yard’s name comes from a historic inn sign depicting the Virgin Mary’s bleeding heart. Urban legends about Lady Elizabeth Hatton’s murder add to its Gothic atmosphere.

title: Reading Room
inscription: The iconic circular Reading Room opened in 1857 and served as a scholarly hub for Victorian writers. A Wikiversity list of readers includes Charles Dickens among its notable users.
lead_subject_bio: Although he is not documented as a daily reader, the British Museum Reading Room represented the intellectual milieu of Victorian London. Its atmosphere of “quiet study under the great dome” influenced many authors and provides insight into the research culture of Dickens’s era.

title: The Good Mixer
inscription: Legendary pub where Britpop stars drank and where the Oasis v Blur rivalry reportedly began. Regulars included members of Blur, Oasis, Elastica, Menswear and even Amy Winehouse.
lead_subject_bio: The Good Mixer’s website notes that the pub is a legendary Camden pub known for hosting musicians of the 1990s Britpop era, including Alan McGee, Jarvis Cocker, Suggs and Elastica. CAMRA adds that it was the scene of the first blow in the Oasis‑Blur feud when Noel Gallagher allegedly told Graham Coxon: “Nice music, s**t clothes.”; Elastica signed a record deal here and Menswear supposedly formed at the bar. A Londonist map explains that this story helped cement the pub’s place in Britpop lore.

title: The Laurel Tree
inscription: Birthplace of the Blow Up club night, often described as the cradle of Britpop; early hangout of Blur, Elastica, Pulp & Suede.
lead_subject_bio: The Shady Old Lady site identifies the pub (now a BrewDog bar) as formerly the Laurel Tree where DJ Paul Tunkin started the Blow Up club night in 1993; it attracted Britpop legends Blur, Elastica, Suede and Pulp, and Melody Maker dubbed it “the club that changed the world”. Pubwiki confirms that since 2011 the building has been a BrewDog bar.

title: Dingwalls
inscription: Influential 500‑capacity venue that hosted indie and Britpop acts; site where the band My Life Story secured a record deal.
address: East Yard, 11 Camden Lock Pl, London NW1 8AL
lead_subject_bio: Dingwalls is a canal‑side club. In 1996, My Life Story announced a series of gigs at the venue; the shows were so successful that several record labels offered them deals and they eventually signed with Parlophone. Travel writer Globalhelpswap notes that, like the Good Mixer, Dingwalls is an iconic live‑music venue that hosted legendary gigs.

title: Dublin Castle
inscription: Long‑running pub‑venue that helped launch Britpop and continues to host new bands.
lead_subject_bio: Visit London calls The Dublin Castle a “second home to Madness” and notes that the pub helped launch Britpop and now acts as a haven for indie kids, hosting up‑and‑coming bands nightly.

title: The Falcon
inscription: One of the most influential early‑1990s venues; hub of Britpop and shoegaze scenes; now flats.
lead_subject_bio: The Falcon was a key venue where many bands got their start. A history of the pub notes that it became one of the most influential venues of the early 1990s and a hub of London’s Britpop and shoegaze scenes; early performers included Bands and musicians such as Blur (then named Seymour), Pulp, Lush, Slowdive, Inspiral Carpets, Suede, The Stereophonics, Feeder, Doves, PJ Harvey, Travis, Muse, Catatonia, Teenage Fanclub, and Coldplay all played there early in their careers. The Verve's second time performing in London was at the pub. On 22 October 1993, after signing to Creation Records and Sony at the latter's headquarters, Oasis went to Whiteout's concert at The Falcon at which they played an unplanned and shambolic set.The venue closed in 2002, but the building can still be seen.

title: Camden Palace (now KOKO)
inscription: Historic theatre and club where Britpop acts and other famous artists performed.
lead_subject_bio: subTOURING recounts that the theatre opened in 1900, became The Music Machine (home to punk), then Camden Palace, and reopened as KOKO in 2005. Since reopening, artists such as Noel Gallagher (performing a surprise set with Kasabian and Coldplay), Bloc Party, Amy Winehouse and The Killers have played here.

title: Food Records office
inscription: Record label behind Blur; part of Camden’s label scene.
lead_subject_bio: A listing for Blur’s Parklife CD notes that for more information about Food Records one should write to 172A Arlington Road, Camden NW1 7HL—this was the label’s mailing address. Air Mail’s article on Britpop history states that Food Records (Blur’s label) was based on Arlington Road off Parkway.

title: Creation Records HQ
inscription: Label that signed Oasis.
lead_subject_bio: Londonist’s Oasis map notes that Creation Records’ headquarters were at 109 Regent’s Park Road. Oasis members visited the office, though they were more often in the nearby Pembroke Castle pub. Camden Market’s guide adds that Creation moved their HQ here, making Primrose Hill a centre for the 1990s music scene.

title: Pembroke Castle
inscription: Local pub for the Gallagher brothers; part of the Primrose Hill social scene.
lead_subject_bio: Camden Market notes that the Gallagher brothers loved a pint at the Pembroke Castle, which is moments away from Creation Records’ HQ and was their local.

title: Supernova Heights
inscription: Noel Gallagher’s famous party house.
lead_subject_bio: Londonist describes Supernova Heights as Noel Gallagher’s “rock ’n’ roll palace”. The article notes that he soundproofed the Georgian terrace and even emblazoned “Supernova Heights” above the door; the house became a centre of raucous parties where celebrities like Kate Moss stayed. The NME article cited by Londonist recalls the house being full of supermodels and conspiracy‑theory chatter.

title: Noel’s first Camden flat
inscription: The flat where Noel Gallagher learned he was a millionaire.
lead_subject_bio: Camden Market notes that Noel Gallagher’s first Camden home was 88 Albert Street; he was living here when he received the phone call telling him he was officially a millionaire.

title: Abbey Road Studios
inscription: World‑famous studio where Oasis recorded parts of Be Here Now.
address: 3 Abbey Road, St John’s Wood NW8 9AY
lead_subject_bio: Londonist’s Oasis map explains that Oasis recorded some of their third album Be Here Now at Abbey Road Studios in Maida Vale; neighbours complained about the noise and the band left soon after.
